, women played key roles in technological and economic developments during the long precolonial period. Female political leaders were as common as male rulers, and women, especially mothers, were central to religious ceremonies and beliefs. These conclusions contribute a new and critical element to our understanding of Africa's precolonial history. Christine Saidi is Assistant Professor of History at Kutztown University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomenzAfrica, CentralxHistory. 0aWomenzAfrica, EastxHistory. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / African.2bisacsh  afeminism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781580467575?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580467575423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580467575/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles